Simplify $16\cdot \frac{1}{4}$ plus the reciprocal of $-\frac{1}{2}$.

}

\large

\textbf{Answer:} First, we simplify $16\cdot \frac{1}{4}$. Note that $16$ can be written as $16=4\cdot 4$. Then, we can group the pair of reciprocals and multiply as follows:\begin{align*}16\cdot \frac{1}{4}&=4\cdot 4\cdot \frac{1}{4} \\ &=4\cdot \frac{1}{4}\cdot 4 \\ &=\left(4\cdot \frac{1}{4}\right)\cdot 4 \\ &=1\cdot 4\\ &=4.\end{align*}Next, recall that $-\frac{1}{x}=\frac{1}{-x}$, for any nonzero number $x$, the reciprocal of any nonzero number $x$ is $\frac{1}{x}$, and $\frac{1}{\frac{1}{x}}=x$, for any nonzero number $x$. We find that the reciprocal of $-\frac{1}{2}=\frac{1}{-2}$ is $\frac{1}{\frac{1}{-2}}=-2$. Now, we just have to substitute back into the original equation and do the addition. We have\begin{align*}16\cdot \frac{1}{4}+\left(\frac{1}{-\frac{1}{2}}\right)&=4+(-2) \\ &=4-2 \\ &=\boxed{2}.\end{align*}

